A stack is a linear data structure that stores a sequence of elements in a top-down, first-in, last-out (FILO) manner. It is composed of a linked list of nodes, each of which contains an element and a reference to the node above it. When an element is pushed onto the stack, it is appended to the end of the list, and the reference to the new top node is returned to the caller. Similarly, when an element is popped from the stack, it is removed from the top node and its reference is returned to the caller.

Both data structures are based on the concept of a Last-in, first-out (LIFO) or First-in, first-out (FIFO) operation, where the newest or the oldest element is the one that is processed first. The LIFO and FIFO operations can be used to implement various algorithms, such as the stack and queue algorithms, which are often used for implementing priority queues, FIFO queues and other ordered data structures.

